data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current code uses `Assert.IsTrue` for everything, which gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False."

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with useful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all items satisfy a condition
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), 
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), 
        "Expected an Admin user in results");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure shows *"Expected: 3, Actual: 1"* instead of just *"True was False"*
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections: `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `Contains`, `AreEqual` (order-sensitive), `AreEquivalent` (order-insensitive)
- **Message parameters** — always add a message string to `Assert.IsTrue` so failures are diagnosable
- **`users.Count > 0`** is redundant when you already assert `== 3`
- **Avoid `Single()` for assertions** — it throws `InvalidOperationException`, not a proper test failure. Use `Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(...))` or check the count instead.

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);      // same items, same order
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
```

If you're open to a third-party library, **FluentAssertions** makes this even cleaner:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
